# Microblink Verify on Google Cloud Marketplace

### **Overview**

BlinkID Verify extracts the data and performs multiple security checks and inspections on government-issued identity documents.

Check identity documents more confidently to protect your business from fraud without disrupting the user experience.

BlinkID Verify is a kubernetes server side solution for remotely verifying identity document authenticity

### **Installation**

You can use [Google Cloud Shell](https://cloud.google.com/shell/) or a local workstation to follow the steps below.

[![][image2]](https://cloud.google.com/shell/)

#### **Prerequisites**

##### **Set up command-line tools**

You'll need the following tools in your development environment. If you are using Cloud Shell, `gcloud`, `kubectl`, `helm`, `Docker`, and `Git` are installed in your environment by default.

* [Gcloud](https://cloud.google.com/sdk/gcloud/)  
* [kubectl](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/overview/)  
* [docker](https://docs.docker.com/install/)  
* [git](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git)  
* [helm](https://helm.sh/)

##### **Google Cloud login and create cluster**

You'll need to login into GCloud and create a cluster. More information on the steps can be found on the following pages:

* [Login](https://cloud.google.com/sdk/gcloud/reference/auth/login)  
* [Create cluster](https://cloud.google.com/sdk/gcloud/reference/container/clusters/create)

To create a cluster with default configuration, please use the following commands.

First we’ll list out all of the active projects, check which one is currently in scope in change if necessary

```
gcloud projects listgcloud config get-value project gcloud config set project PROJECT_ID
```

You need to check that Kubernetes Engine API is enabled by running

```
gcloud services list --enabled
```

After that, you can create a cluster, this is an example with minimal and default configuration, for more options, please check the documentation linked above.

```
gcloud container clusters create sample-microblink-cluster
```

Run the following command, so that the cluster credentials are saved locally (\~/.kube/config) where kubectl can use them as well

```
gcloud container clusters get-credentials PROJECT_NAME
```

Testing that kubectl can access the cluster and get the namespace needed for the GUI deployment, please run:

```
kubectl config view | grep namespace
```

##### **Install Postgres**

It’s recommended to use local deployment, but you can use an external postgres as well.

* [Create and manage databases](https://cloud.google.com/sql/docs/postgres/create-manage-databases)


#### **Installation via Google Cloud Marketplace GUI**

Please go to the Google Cloud Marketplace entry for Microblink BlinkID Verify.  
You will need the following information to go through the setup process.

* Project name  
* Cluster namespace  
* License key  
* Database information  
  * Host (IP address, most commonly internal IP)  
  * Username  
  * Password

### **Upgrade**

After the solution has been deployed, you can upgrade to the latest version with the following command

```
helm upgrade -i PROJECT_NAME microblink/microblink-doc-ver --reuse-values
```

###  **Uninstall**

To uninstall the project, please run the following command

```
helm uninstall PROJECT_NAME
```
